description.text:
This is Randofo. A very cool and simple robot created by Randy Sarafan (His nick is Randofo in Instructables)

The original project uses Standar Servos from Radioshack. I created my own version of the body to use futaba 3003 motors or similar and Arduino UNO or similar boards

I also created a hardware control using Icestudio and the Icezum Alhambra, an open source FPGA board.

Assembly

I reccomend to follow the original instructions of instructables:

http://www.instructables.com/id/3D-Printed-Robot/

The only difference is the electronic part. In this version you directly have the PCB holes for Arduino UNO or similar.

Programming

  • In the case of an Arduino, you can use the original Arduino code. It's simple but it works!

  • In the case that you are using an Icezum Alhambra FPGA board you have the hardware in the format of an Icestudio file. You can easily change the values of the roms that controls the servomotor movements using the program oscillator_rom_generator.py

Notes:

Print pieces on their side as shown in photo.

I also used the "Screw and Knurled Knob" and the "Clamp Protector" from Johann517's original design in https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1673030 You will need to print those two items as well.

How to Use:

Assemble the 4 pieces as shown in the photos and fit them around the X-axis motor. When used, this jig will pull the stepper motor toward the end of the X-axis rod assy and thus tension the x-axis belt.

Lightly tighten the knurled knob to securely hold the jig in place BEFORE loosening the 4 screws holding the stepper motor in position. The stepper must be loose enough to be moved, but not so much that it pivots on its mounting bolts and jams. Loosen the two outside bolts a bit more than the inside two bolts. ("Inside" is closer to the center of the printer.)

Once the stepper motor is loose, tighten the knurled knob to tension the X-axis belt. The jig will bow slightly as it is tightened. After the belt is tensioned re-tighten the 4 stepper motor mounting screws to lock the motor in place. When tightening the 4 stepper mounting bolts, tighten the inside two bolts first, then tighten the outside two. Lastly, loosen the knurled knob and remove the jig.

Done.

title: Cable Strain Relief for Anet A8 Heat Bed

description.text:
Strain relief for Anet A8 Heat Bed

This is based on the idea linked in the remix, but I wanted to make one from scratch using OpenSCAD and that would work with the Connector Housing I designed here:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2428313.

This bracket fixes to the top of the carriage - above the bearing housing and provides a simple mechanism to fix the cable loom near to the Connector to prevent additional movement. It works for me and the design file is here in OpenSCAD so you can take and it and change as you wish.

Using this and the Connector Housing you should not need to solder ("hack") your heat bed connector any more; honestly, some of the soldering jobs I have seen make me shudder.

NB: In the OpenSCAD design file I am including a custom library. The library contains a simple function to create cubes with rounded corners wich I am using in this design. The function is below:

// A function I use a lot to create a cuboid shape with rounded corners
module roundedCube(xdim,ydim,zdim,rdim) {
    hull() {
        translate([rdim,rdim,0]) cylinder(r=rdim,h=zdim);
        translate([xdim-rdim,rdim,0]) cylinder(r=rdim,h=zdim);
        translate([rdim,ydim-rdim,0]) cylinder(r=rdim,h=zdim);
        translate([xdim-rdim,ydim-rdim,0]) cylinder(r=rdim,h=zdim);
    }
}

title: Hydroponics Net Cup / Pot System for 4inch PVC Pipe

description.text:
Hydroponic Net cup/pot System for 4" PVC Pipe

Start your plants off first in the smaller net cups in a cloner/nursery. Once you are ready to move your plants to your 4" PVC pipe hydroponics system, you simply use the cap + grommet pieces that mounts on the PVC tube.

One of the main advantages of a hydroponic system is the ability to keep things clean which reduces the number of pests in your garden. I have seen a lot of 4" PVC type systems but in most of them there are large gaping holes where the net pots are drilled. This is no good as it lets sunlight, bugs, dirt direct access to the roots. With this design my goal was to create a clean interface between the net cups and the PVC tubing.

Note: This design is for v2 of my hydroponic grow which has not happened yet, I have not installed these yet, they are only a proof of concept currently.. If you need a special pipe diameter I may be able to adapt the design to your specifications. Let me know!

Related Designs:

description.text:
This is a holder for the Anet A8 mainboard and two mosfets of the "not so usual" kind.

In my infinite wisdom (I wish) I bought the "wrong" mosfet modules. Not the ones everyone seems to use for their Anet A8s but the ones where input and output connectors are on opposite sides of the modules instead of the same side.

Also they have different measurements than the usual ones. I measured 45mm by 70mm so the mounts and nice boxes with covers won't fit. I think the usual mosfets have 50mm by 60mm or something.

So if you by any chance made the same mistake I did - give this a try.

I marked this a "work in progress" as I'm probably gonna rebuild this into an enclosure with a 120mm fan mount or something in the future. Just needed a quick fix for now, so the mosfets don't lie around on the table. Works for that.

Notes:

You'll need a few screws that go into the plastic mounts for the mosfets. I used

8x 3.5mm x 10mm philips pan head screws

At least I think that's what they're called in english.
The mainboard is fastened with the original screws, the original spacers aren't needed anymore.

(Optional) Cleanup

If your printer does a lot of stringing (mine isn't properly set up yet, so it does), you'll want to clean up the strings between the mounts. But mostly for looks.

(probably NOT optional) fix screw holes for mainboard

I designed the holes to be exactly 3mm in diameter. My printer of course didn't want to print it exactly that way, so I had to widen the holes a bit. Simply used a 3mm drill, went through once, done. Your mileage may vary, of course. If your printer is finely adjusted, it might just work without this step or with some vigorously screwing that screw in instead.

Note: no drilling needed for the mosfet screw holes. Those screws should eat into the mount anyway, so might just screw them in without drilling. I did.

Needed it, didn't find it, thought I'd give it a try

So... I measured the hole distances for the mainboard and my mosfets, gave a bit of distance between them (as much as I could without making it unnecessary difficult to attach the cables later on) and designed those mounts from tubes. After that I added all those bars to fit the mounts together and as a last step I added the holes - so they go through the bars, too.

As I mentioned above, this is by no means a fine piece of engineering, just a quick and dirty hack to get the mosfets onto the printer and off the table.

Probably isn't the most stable thing, either, so best handle with care after printing.

description.text:
Inspired by by the Badwolf GT2B controller i decided to make my own design.

This thing is not super pretty, but i found it more comfy, and it requires less hassle to put together, + the trigger is adjustable.

One of the key features about this controller is that the GT2B board and battery fits inside without any modifications.

This design works well, but is far from perfect, i will probably make a updated design later.

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

100%

Notes:

Simply print the case with 100% infill.

100% infill seems crazy, but it gives the controller really good stability, otherwise it will feel rather flimsy. The idea is that the 2mm walls need to be filled, if they are not, then it will feel flimsy.

I had problems with layer adhesion using layer-heights > 0.3mm, using my 0.5mm nozzle.
So i printed min at 0.2mm layer height.

Attaching the trigger

The trigger is fastened with a M3 screw, M3 nut and matching washers.

The washers are super important, otherwise you will squish the plastic and ruin the print, so make sure you use washers!

It should be pretty straight forward, there is only one screw-hole. :)

OPTIONAL - Light diffusing

I used a bit of hot glue to diffuse the light holes, otherwise they will be super bright.

Hold a piece of plastic candy wrapper on the inside of the light holes, then pour some glue into it, then quickly dip you finger in a bit of water and smooth out the glue for a good finish.

Then carefully peal off the candy wrapper.

Don be afraid to fail, the glue is fairly easy to clean up for a retry.

The interior

Duct-tape the battery connector from the GT2B controller base to the battery.
SUPER IMPORTANT - make sure + and - matches up on the connector and battery.

Connect the trigger and battery to the GT2B main board.

Fit the GT2B board in the top case with the button holes, and dash it with a bit of hot glue to make it stick.

Then put some hot-glue on the connectors on the top case and close the case.

And you are done!

Random notes / things i bodged

  • If you take apart the controller later, be careful if you hot-glued the main board to the top piece. I had the power switch come off when i pulled it out (i managed to squeeze it back on).

  • The antenna wire is not soldered particularly durable, mine fell off while i was manhandling it and i had to solder it back on. You can secure it better if you give it a dash of hot-glue around the solder joints.

title: X endstop trigger for FFCP when printing without right extruder

description.text:
When only printing with one nozzle on the Flashforge Creator Pro or similar printer, you can improve print quality considerably by removing the unused heavy extruder stepper motor. Doing so will reduce the weight of the carriage and help to reduce ringing and ripple artifacts on your print. It is much easier to remove the right stepper, so usually you would do single extrusion prints with your left extruder. However, the right stepper motor is also used to trigger the X endstop, so if you remove it, you must put something in place. I like the dummy stepper by race12001, but still found it too large, therefore I made this more minimal but still sturdy version that is just large enough to trigger the switch. It is easily mounted with the same screws as the stepper.

I provide two versions, one that accepts 5x5 mm M3 brass inserts, and one with direct holes. The brass inserts are recommended, but simply threading the screws into the direct holes should also work, although you risk stripping the holes if you regularly mount and unmount this part.
Another variation omits the extra tab that covers the hot-end hole. This tab may help to avoid that dust or dirt ends up in the hole, although this wouldn't be a problem if you also unscrew the right nozzle when not using it.

Overview This project was born because I have been building my own quadcopters for a few years now and I wanted to use my experience in this field to build another type of radio-controlled machine. I wanted to build something bigger than a drone while adapting the basic components of a radio control vehicle (motors, electronic speed controllers, receiver and radio transmitter and batteries.). Having done quite a lot of skateboarding in my teenage years, I quickly considered the feasibility of propelling skateboard thanks to the electronic components that I used to use. Having to find similar projects and the necessary components, I have to realize all the prototyping in 3D printing. I launched version 1 of my project "PEX Board" at the end of July 2017, and I now intend to realize a series of improvements and mods to propose different configurations and extend the possibilities of this open-source electric skateboard. I among other things to make a waterproof version with larger off-road wheels for the winter. I live in Canada... and I don't want to wait 6 months to ride :) The fun part of the project is that you can print it if you want (by using your own 3D printer, by looking for local printers on 3Dhubs.com or by ordering me the parts directly.) you can build it without any soldering if you want and once you have sourced all the parts, it can be build and configurated in a weekend. I have published a tutorial to explain how to build it from A to Z.

Introduction This is an open source electric longboard easy to build and fun to ride.
The purpose of this page is to detail all the required parts and steps to build your own electric longboard. Budget for mechanical parts and electric components: $220 to $300 (USD)

  • Learn how to ride a longboard first, it’s very important to learn skateboard basics before to start this project. This will prevent you from injuring yourself by taming the engine’s propulsion in addition to attempting to manage your balance and steering.

  • This project requires tools and specific equipment. I personally add to use a soldering station because my batteries’ connectors were not standard and I had to use a hot glue gun, a hex key set, an electric screwdriver, my rotary tool to adapt my truck to my motor mount and to create a handle in my deck. These tools could be totally optional and I will detail one setup below that require just some tapes, screws, hex keys and sockets. In addition, you can check the list of tool that I would suggest to any hobbyist. I would like to recommend to buy a skateboard tool as it brings together all the socket sizes needed to set your trucks and wheels and a screwdriver.

title: Eachine Aurora 100 FPV Racing Quad Upgrade Kit & Mods: YOUR FIRST DRONE
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
First, a little backstory...

I got my Aurora 100 brushless micro quad from Banggood in early 2017. Since then, I've grown to absolutely love it! Though others may disagree, I think the Aurora 100 is your best option as a first racing drone. First off, the Aurora is small. I've owned quite a few larger drones within the 180-500 class and they are outright dangerous! Not saying that the Aurora can't seriously hurt somebody or the walls of your house, but it's a LOT safer than the dangerous shredder of a 180 class. If you're new, you'll be crashing often and that means crashing safely. Furthermore, it can be tricky getting used to FPV and it would be a tragedy to accidentally turn somebody, or their dog, into a red slushie. But there's also strength and power to take into account. With the right upgrades (which I've listed in this post), you can turn your Aurora 100 into the ultimate flying machine. To give you an idea, I've been running the same props, motors, and frame for the last two months; and I'm not even a very good pilot!

The 3D printed modifications and upgrades are listed below:

-Hybrid PLA & TPU Frame With Integrated Motor Guards Though not as strong as carbon fiber, these "hybrid frames" are highly durable and definitely worth a try for low budget fliers. The Aurora 100 ships with a very weak stock frame (only 1.5mm thick carbon fiber) that will break easily. If you're interested in an infinite supply of cheap 3D printable frames that are STRONGER THAN THE STOCK FRAME and have integrated motor guards, you've come to the right place! The main thing I love about these frames is that they never fully break. When you slam into a street light at 40mph, the arm will flex and the PLA core will snap, but the arm will still stay fully attached, protecting your motor wires. I can't count the number of motors that got their wires ripped out because the arm of my carbon frame flew off! (I literally have a 1104 motor graveyard) Also, they have integrated motor guards which protect your motors from hard hits that can dislodge the magnets glued to your rotor (outside part of the motor). As for strength, one of my friends once said, "these frames are literally indestructible." Realistically, they can, and will, break, but it's definitely a great, inexpensive way to go. Note that this print does require a dual extruder printer. I also plan to start selling them in bulk on eBay sooner or later.

-Motor guards (for 1103/4/5/6) protect the not-so-durable stock Eachine motors. If you're low budget like me, you don't want to (or can't) invest the $60 in a set of nice, durable motors. I've found the stock motors more than adequate when properly protected. Though these motor guards may add a significant amount of weight to your build, they are almost essential to using the stock motors. Also, even with all of these mods, my Aurora totally rips! Note that there are clockwise (CW) and counterclockwise (CCW) motor guards. For more info on the motor guards, see my other post.

-ATX03 VTX and camera mount allows you to install an upgraded ATX03 video transmitter! If you ever decide to race your Aurora at any events, you'll need a VTX capable of more than the puny 25mw the stock transmitter outputs (trust me, I tried). Even if you're on a different channel, the 200mw VTXs of the other larger quads will give you signal hell. The Eachine ATX03 video transmitter (VTX) allows you to select not only the channel, but also select the power at either 25mw, 50mw, or 200mw! Moreover, the ATX03 has an IPEX port, allowing you to plug in a durable whip antenna. The common cloverleaf antenna that most micro FPV rigs come with is very fragile and probably won't survive much, but a whip antenna will last forever.

Okay, now let's talk about the 3D printed parts. It consists simply of two side panels which slide over your two front red aluminum standoffs. The ATX03 then slides in! These panels also provide great protection against annoying grass bits and other stuff that your props may fling into your flight controller (FC) stack.

-Camera Locks The camera locks are definitely some of the smaller mods that I've installed but do serve a useful purpose. Because the ATX03 is just a VTX, you'll need to install an external camera. With the stock VTX and camera rig, the whole thing was pinched between the carbon fiber and aluminum camera mount. This made sure that your camera didn't slide around during flight. When using an external camera, it can slide around in its place especially when trying to put on a lens cap! These two little pieces slide into the rectangular slots on the side of the aluminum camera mount and lock your camera in place so it doesn't slide out when you install your lens cap! If you're suffering from vibration issues, print them in TPU to help reduce vibrations transferred to your camera!

-Antenna Guard and Roll Bar If you're one of those people who love cloverleaf antennas and just can't bear to give them up to a dipole, you're in luck! These antenna guards are large enough to fit most small cloverleaf antennas that don't have a long coaxial cable (the wire connecting the SMA connector to the antenna). Even if you're not running a cloverleaf, whip antennas can break! Better be safe than sorry!

These antenna guards also work as great roll bars. The top plate of most quads is known to be that part that will rarely, or never, break. This is sort of true with the Aurora. When you're flying fast, your quad will be tilted very far forward, meaning if you crash, you're more likely damage the top of your quad than when flying at slower speeds. Also, if you ever fly face first into a tree, there's a chance that your Aurora may fall upside down onto the pavement. By attaching these antenna guards, you allow them to break instead of your top plate. I've included both .STL and .SVG files for the antenna guards as some of you may want to try to CNC them out of carbon fiber. I suggest printing them in either polycarbonate, if your printer can handle it, or TPU.

-The Original Aurora Base Plate If you own a 3D printer, CNC, or laser cutter, I've included .STL and .SVG files for my rendition of the original Aurora baseplate! It's not very strong in PLA (the hybrid frame is much more durable), but it's nearly indestructible when CNC'd in 2.5mm carbon fiber.

My current rig (August 2017): This is what I'm currently running and have been running for the last few months. I've tinkered with it quite a bit and think that I've hit the "sweet spot."
-Stock Minicube Flight Controller, ESC (10A), and Receiver Stack 20mmx20mm
-Stock Eachine 7500kv 1104 Motors
-Stock Eachine 450mah 2s 80c LiPo
-Upgraded 2.5mm Carbon Fiber Base Plate
-1000tvl 1.2g 120 Degree CMOS Camera
-Eachine ATX03 Video and Audio Transmitter (with whip antenna)
-Gemfan 2035 Polycarbonate "Indestructible" Propellers (these live up to their name) Note that I run these only about 1/2 the time I fly. After extreme crashes (often), I replace all four props with the ones listed below. I'm still deciding which ones are best. These are great because they are well balanced but bend easily. You'll just need to bend them back after every crash.

After a solid crash into a streetlight, you can expect to break at least a blade or two. Sadly, about 1/2 of these props arrive very poorly balanced to the point where it's nearly unflyable due to the amount of noise this creates on the video feed (due to vibrations). Make sure to balance them! Lastly, I seem to get a little more thrust from these props and they're also are slightly more efficient (according to the thrust charts).

title: CiiiCooler remix for Wanhao Titan Extruder/V6 mount

description.text: With permission from Pawpawpaw85, I present to you my CiiiCooler remix for the Titan Extruder/V6 mount by bliatun (NOT THE TITAN AERO). Also included a modified fan grill to reclaim the lost X travel on the left side of the bed when using a pancake stepper instead of the stock stepper.

Printer:

Maker Select V2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Supports from print bed only for the remixed CiiiCooler, low enough angle to support the mounting plate part but not so much the cooler's vents are filled. I added the parametric spacer as the original's built in spacer would have needed everywhere support which would mess up the interior of the cooler in the print orientation needed. PETG or ABS recommended as the ends of the cooler are only a mm or 2 from the block, it just barely clears if you have the silicon sock, no idea how different the clone V6's are. You will also need to bend the wires for the heater cartridge quite a bit for clearance (see photo above).

For the Fan grill you must use a pancake stepper like https://www.omc-stepperonline.com/hybrid-stepper-motor/nema-17-bipolar-18deg-18ncm-255ozin-07a-29v-42x42x25mm-4-wires-17hs10-0704s.html. Install the limit switch last as the switch's wires will get in the way of tightening the bolt that holds the fan and cooler to the extruder mount. I made it so it gets maximum clearance on MY setup with the pancake stepper, if it doesn't engage switch when homing X make sure the switch's metal lever is pointed downwards (pivot on top) and maybe stick something on the X axis stepper so it engages the switch sooner. Please also note it only seems to slice properly with Cura, have not been able to fix that issue.

For the CiiiCooler I literally just cut off sections I didn't need in TinkerCad and added random stuff to fill holes then Netfabb'ed to make it printable. Approved version was based on suggestions by Pawpawpaw85 to minimize performance drop, though no computer aided testing has been done I feel it works great =D Fan grill was modded in TinkerCad with adjustments made so my setup could get maximum travel, use with caution. Spacer was made with https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2363303

description.text:
First, thank you to Lucashayes for such a simple, elegant solution for mounting the E3D Titan extruder in the stock CR-10 extruder location.

This is just a quick remix of this thing for those of you that have the 'full size' (59Ncm) stepper motor driving your Titan extruder (for instance, MatterHackers doesn't have the 'pancake' 12Ncm stepper motors, they only offer the full size one). The full size steppers are just a bit too long to use the original sized mount with Lucashayes design, so this extends the stepper further away from gantry so it doesn't bottom out against the (left side) inner roller bolt and nut.

You will need to use (just like Lucashayes original) 4x M3 nuts, and 4x M3 x 6mm, or M3 x 8mm machine screws for this mount to work for you.

description.text: This is a slight adjustment to the Z Axis motor mount I needed after installing the "Creality CR-10 Wire management, Strain relief and Glass holder" https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2328449 which I found impacted the corner of the motoer mount, precluding full and unobstructed Y Axis travel. Notes:

I print all Support elements that might be exposed to any stresses, out of ABS but we're not printing a fan shroud or anything that would be exposed to any meaningful heat, so PLA should be fine too.

Z Axis Motor mount instalation

Motor mount installation is a bit of a pain in the add. It's easier if you disconnect the Z Axis lead screw, in order gein straight-on access to the bolts that hold the motor mount in place. You may be able to remove the original mount without removing the lead screw but you'll likely be unable to apply enough straight-on pressure to tighten the bolts into the frame.

As such, do this:
1.) Loosen the two lower set screws in the X axis lead screw coupler, and push the coupler and screw up off the motor shaft, allowing it to hang freely as you work.

2.) unscrew the bolts holding the original motor mount to the frame

3.) Unscrew the bolts holding the original motor mount to the motor.

4.) Secure the new motor mount to the motor

5.) Position the motor in place against the frame, and secure it in place using the frame bolts through the new motor mount.

6.) slide the lead screw coupler down over the Y Axis motor shaft, taking care not to allow the coupler to touch the motor housing (there has to be a few millimeters of space there) and re-tighten the two bottom set screws in the lead screw coupler.

Done! That wasn't so bad, was it?

Designed in OnShape

This is a trivial adjustment but if you want to mess with it further you can do so here: https://cad.onshape.com/documents/0c57ff6b1dea63911580d8e6/w/7403f359e07a658ad5a24d65/e/ae9b678c9e5875d5cd993057

You'll note that the full geometry was imported into onShape. This was accomplished from the motor mount STL file from which this object was remixed, by first importing the STL into FreeCAD, and exporting a STEP file, which was then imported into onShape. This facilitated boolean operations, which is really all that was needed to accomplish this remix.

Finishing and preparing to fly the Glider model 
 Glue the rubber band launching hook in the pocket below the nose of the plane using CA glue.

 Apply a small amount of glue to the pockets between the wings and the fuselage.  I use a wooden toothpick to make sure the glue gets down into the pockets.  Then use a medium sized binder clip to hold the wings tight to the fuselage while the glue dries.

Using a substantial rubber-band attached to a stick or dowel draw the plane back holding the rudder and release it to send it flying! description.text:
I know what you're thinking, "there are no dice in SORRY!". The D12 is a game changer. The luck of the roll vs the fate of a set deck of cards.

The star=SORRY is so Parker Brothers doesn't send a C&D...

Try our heads up version:
-Each player controls two sets of pawns.
-Start with a pawn in the opposite corner from each start area.
-2 dice are rolled. Each set of pawns gets one move from the dice. If a 2 is rolled, only the pawn set that used the 2 gets another roll.
-An 11 can be used to swap a pawn between your own two sets or your opponents sets.
-You can bump your own team [one set hits another] back to start.
-You must use a move if you can. i.e. you have one set all at home and one pawn [second set] in the safe zone [the other 3 are in start or home]. You roll a 8 and 4. You can't use the 8 so you must move the pawn back four spaces.
-If one dice is rolled off the table you lose your whole turn
-To win the game, get all pawns from both sets to home.
-This variation has been play tested for years [we have a SORRY table]. All of the options with the two dice and eight pawns makes for a fun filled game. Give it a go!

*Jumbo sized 27mm tall

"#burnYourCards"

Notes:

Use 100% infill on the dice to get proper weight. Supports are needed to keep the details crisp.

If you have good bed adhesion, print the numbers without a brim.

***The standalone 1's and the 1's from the 10,11 & 12 are different width. Don't mix them up when removing them from the bed.

Superglue the numbers and pips into the D12. Some force is needed to seat them properly.

Clean up uneven print areas [bottom of the print brim edge] with sandpaper/x-acto blade. Polish sanded areas with a butane lighter.

description.text: 4D Cube in 3D To fully understand I recommend reading this.

To produce this object I used a common editor called blender. First I created a basic cube with a smaller cube inside. I extruded the faces of the smaller cube to the outside of the larger cube while locking the extrusion to the axis the face was pointing to. With the new object inside, I used the boolean tool to remove the area that it shared with the big cube and removed it. This left be with a solid "wireframe" like cube. I duplicated this object and shifted it using the blender grid. Join these cubes into one object. Onces that was done, I joined all of the corners using the edit tools and created joining vertices, then faces from those vertices. Don't fill the ends that are inside the cubes yet. (Its hard to get to them if you do) The next bit is tricky. I highlight all of the new "joints" that aren't completely solid and unjoin them from the object. (Use the blender manual to attempt this) I filled in the empty ends where the cubes once existed without moving it on the scene! You can now use boolean logic to join this into the cubes and clean up any faces that may become problematic using the edit tools. *Note Dimensions don't matter much in this. You can scale my model or make your own with any sizes you like.

These are the spotter buttons I used at Weston Park Dronefest 2017.

Many race control software packages (including the free Laps Free from RCTiming.com) allow you to use the number keys to simulate competitors crossing the finish line, or even to manually register missed laps should a competitor's transponder work unreliably.

They can be made very cheaply from readily available components and used where the cost of lap timing systems is prohibitively expensive.

• 1x arduino pro micro - I chose this one because it has an in-built micro-USB port, and works with the keyboard library to turn it into a standard HID device.
  • 8x NO momentary switches - I used 12mm red leaf-contact switches. They had horrendous amounts of bounce but they were cheap!
  • 2x rear-mount RJ45 sockets with locator flanges - The pin spacing on these is weird so we'll be soldering wires directly from the leads to the arduino.
  • 1x 8-port RJ45 patch panel - Not essential to the functionality but a heavy box will help keep it in one place and reduce the number of wires coming from Race Control.
  • 8x 5m UTP cables (coloured) - To run between the patch panel and the button wands. Using standard electronics colours will help identify the correct buttons from a distance.
  • 2x 10m UTP cables (black) - To run between the arduino and the patch panel. They don't have to be black, but you don't want to confuse them with the other cables.
arduino sketch 
/* Provide buttons to trigger the manual lap counting
 * in race control software that supports this feature.
 */
#include <Bounce2.h>
#include <Keyboard.h>

typedef struct
{
  int pin;
  char key;
} lapCountBtnType;

lapCountBtnType lapCountBtns[] = 
{
  {6, '1'},   // keys 1-4 on left of board
  {7, '4'},
  {8, '3'},
  {9, '2'},
  {15, '5'},  // keys 5-8 on right of board
  {14, '8'},
  {16, '6'},
  {10, '7'}
};
//int numBtns = 8;
int numBtns = sizeof(lapCountBtns) / sizeof(lapCountBtns[0]);
int debounceInterval = 10;  // milliseconds

Bounce * debouncer = new Bounce[numBtns];

#define LED_PIN 17

void setup()
{
  for (int i=0; i<numBtns; i++)
  {
    pinMode(lapCountBtns[i].pin, INPUT_PULLUP);
    debouncer[i].attach(lapCountBtns[i].pin);
    debouncer[i].interval(debounceInterval);
  }

  // onboard LED
  pinMode(LED_PIN, OUTPUT);
}

void loop()
{
  for (int i=0; i<numBtns; i++)
  {
    debouncer[i].update();
    if (debouncer[i].fell())
    {
      // issue keypress
      Keyboard.write(lapCountBtns[i].key);
    }
  }
}

Don't forget to grab the Bounce2 library from here:
https://github.com/thomasfredericks/Bounce2

Introduction

Most race control software can accept laps registered manually by pressing the number keys on a keyboard. It occurred to me that if I could extend the number keys and place them in the hands of spotters, then the job of registering missed laps then becomes their responsibility, and this would save me having to yell "WHO JUST CROSSED THE LINE?!" whenever I see one pass without triggering the race control 'beep'.
This is my implementation of that idea, using a simple arduino and some buttons on the ends of long wires.

Features
  • Plug-and-play (no drivers needed).
  • Self-powered (no extra PSU or batteries needed).
  • Supports a flight line up to 10m long, at up to 10m away from Race Control.
  • Requires a minimal increase in cabling at Race Control.
  • Is easy to identify which buttons corresponds to which numbers without having to pick them up.
  • Idiot-proof to the extent that plugging the buttons into the wrong ports will not attribute laps to the wrong competitor
Breakout box

This houses the arduino and two RJ45 sockets. We need two because each UTP cable contains 4 pairs, and we need a pair for each button. I used a different pair for each button so that it would only work if plugged into the correct socket. This prevents accidentally attributing laps to the wrong competitor. It also allows you to test the buttons by bypassing the patch panel and plugging them directly into this little box. The first RJ45 socket registers buttons 1-4, and the second socket registers buttons 5-8.

There's a schematic of which pins go where, but don't worry if you mess it up because you can always correct it in the software. The most important thing is to get the grounds and signal wires soldered correctly. For simplicity, I used the white wires as ground and coloured wires for signal.

Once you're done, simply hot glue the lot together and flash the arduino with the supplied sketch. You can adjust the debounce delay to accommodate the type of switches you're using or as mentioned earlier, re-order the pin/button mappings if you've made a hash of the wiring.

Buttons

The hardest part with these is to find a way to solder the fiddly UTP wires to the switch terminals AND provide some kind of strain relief. I ended up doubling up the whole UTP cable into an 'S' shape inside the wand and tying a knot at the exit end. The knot prevents the cable from pulling out of the wand, and the 'S' bend provides a little slack. I considered using red JST P-type connectors but it sounded like overkill.

Patch panel

The only thing to remember here is to connect the same pairs as we did in the box of tricks to the appropriate numbered ports on the patch panel. Most patch panels use punchdown connectors so this bit should be dead easy - no soldering!

I snipped the RJ45 plugs off one end, stripped the sheathing back to reveal the pairs and punched them down into the patch panel directly. I figured that if I ever need to place the box more than 10m away from Race Control then RJ45 couplers are cheap.

Operation

Connect it all up as per the schematic and connect a USB cable between the breakout box and your laptop. It should detect that a keyboard has been connected and the buttons should send the numbers 1-8 to the computer as if it were a real keyboard. The arduino flashes one of its LEDs (I can't remember which) to indicate when a button press has been detected.

This is a Carbine kit for Airsoft Mk23 SOCOM NBB pistol.
It works with Tokyo Marui, ASG and Stti guns.

I don't own a LAM unit, so I designed the main body to protrude a little bit into the sides of the pistol rail. If you want to mount a LAM unit to the gun, just remove enough material from the sides.

The buttstock mounting portion is designed for Well MB-06 / APS SR-2 / ASG Urban Sniper buffer tube assembly, but you can attach a normal M4 buffer tube to it with a little bit of modification.

Please remember to mention my name if you distribute these files or post it on somewhere else.

If you like what I do, you can leave a tip! It would be highly appreciated!

English (german below):
I didn't liked the huge empty space below the main center screen in a tesla model s/x as it's not really usable and leads to mess. So I found my way how to improve and deal with it.

This sorter fits perfectly into a Tesla Model S / X below the large center screen and keeps things in order. It has openings for:

  • two ballpens,
  • 3 business or parcing cards/tickets,
  • euro parking disc as well as
  • car papers and
  • a place for sunglasses and such...

Because of its sizes a larger 3d printer is necessary. Ultimaker 3 extended and such. Typical printing time is above 30 hours...

2 Kugelschreiber
Parkscheibe (Plastik inkl. Eiskratzer o.ä.)
KFZ-Schein inkl. Lederhülle
Rechts ein Fach für Sonnenbrille & Co.
